def cool_countplot(data=None, x=None, y=None, hue=None, text_size=10):
    ax = sns.countplot(data=data, x=x, hue=hue)
    for p in ax.patches:
        ax.annotate(text=str(int(p.get_height())) + ' (' + '{:.0%}'.format(p.get_height()/data.shape[0]) + ')',
                       xy=(p.get_x()+p.get_width()/2, p.get_height()/2), ha='center', color='black', size=text_size,s="Message")
    return ax

                        [0, 1], inplace=True)
df['region'].replace(['southwest', 'southeast','northwest','northeast'],

Evaluating model accuracy

one of a way to evaluate the performance of a linear regresion model rather than plotting it, using evalution metrices.The essential step in any machine learning model is to evaluate the accuracy of the model. The Mean Squared Error, Mean absolute error, and R-Squared or Coefficient of determination metrics are used to evaluate the performance of the model in regression analysis.

In [21]:
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, r2_score,mean_absolute_error

r_squared = r2_score(test_Y, y_pred)
print('Mean_Squared_Error :' ,mse)
print('r_square_value :',r_squared)
print("Mean Absolute Error : ",mean_absolute_error(y_pred,test_Y))

RANDOM FOREST¶

In [27]:
# RANDOM FOREST
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestRegressor
# creating the model
model = RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators = 40, max_depth = 4, n_jobs = -1)

# feeding the training data to the model
model.fit(train_X, train_Y)
# predicting the test set results
y_pred3 = model.predict(test_X)
In [28]:
# calculating the mean squared error
random_forest_mse = np.mean((test_Y - y_pred3)**2, axis = None)
print("Mean Square Error :", random_forest_mse)
# Calculating the root mean squared error
random_forest_rmse = np.sqrt(random_forest_mse)
print("Root Mean Square Error :", random_forest_rmse)
# Calculating the r2 score
random_forest_r2 = r2_score(test_Y, y_pred3)
print("r_square value :", random_forest_r2)
# Calculating Mean Absalute error
random_forest_mae = mean_absolute_error(test_Y,y_pred3)
print("Mean Absalure Error : ", random_forest_mae)

# Gradient Boost Regression
from sklearn.ensemble import GradientBoostingRegressor

# creating the model
gradient_model = GradientBoostingRegressor(n_estimators = 40, max_depth = 4,)
# fitting the training data in model
gradient_model.fit(train_X,train_Y)
# predicting the test set results
y_pred4 = gradient_model.predict(test_X)
